00:33:47.060 --> 00:33:50.110
thinker, I'm going to venture
into this world of talking

00:33:50.110 --> 00:33:51.900
about the global food system.

00:33:51.900 --> 00:33:55.190
And the fact that we live in a
world where basically, much of

00:33:55.190 --> 00:33:57.730
the world subsists on
eight basic grains.

00:33:57.730 --> 00:33:59.020
And I'm not going to name
them all for you.

00:33:59.020 --> 00:34:00.050
You can probably figure out.

00:34:00.050 --> 00:34:01.576
You can start with rice,
wheat, corn, and

00:34:01.576 --> 00:34:03.560
go on down the list.

00:34:03.560 --> 00:34:07.760
And people eat some 257 other
crops around the world.

00:34:07.760 --> 00:34:09.330
But the big grains are
ones that sustain

00:34:09.330 --> 00:34:11.239
life around the world.

00:34:11.239 --> 00:34:14.850
2008, we had this incredible
event happen, which was that

00:34:14.850 --> 00:34:18.179
we suddenly discovered after 30
or 40 years of assuming we

00:34:18.179 --> 00:34:21.400
had abundant global food supply,
that those grain

00:34:21.400 --> 00:34:23.449
stocks had sort of run out.

00:34:23.449 --> 00:34:27.900
And all these economists woke up
one day, and realized, wow.

00:34:27.900 --> 00:34:28.440
What happened?

00:34:28.440 --> 00:34:31.300
Why are there no sort
of grain stocks?

00:34:31.300 --> 00:34:33.560
And when the grain stocks ran
out, the prices started just

00:34:33.560 --> 00:34:35.350
to spiral out of control.

00:34:35.350 --> 00:34:38.030
And they went up some 300%
around the world.

00:34:38.030 --> 00:34:40.420
Now, think about, if
you're Susan, and

00:34:40.420 --> 00:34:41.940
you're living in Nigeria.

00:34:41.940 --> 00:34:43.679
And you're a subsistence
farmer.

00:34:43.679 --> 00:34:46.080
And you're having a bad
year, as Aarti said.

00:34:46.080 --> 00:34:49.420
