buy food in the local market.

00:34:49.420 --> 00:34:51.179
And you can't produce
enough to eat.

00:34:51.179 --> 00:34:53.290
And the prices have
gone up 300%.

00:34:53.290 --> 00:34:56.610
And on average, you generally
spend 75% to 80% of whatever

00:34:56.610 --> 00:34:58.185
cash you have on food.

00:34:58.185 --> 00:35:01.310
Well, this was like an
impossible situation for poor

00:35:01.310 --> 00:35:02.840
families all over the world.

00:35:02.840 --> 00:35:04.910
It was a little easier, maybe,
if you were a rural

00:35:04.910 --> 00:35:05.870
subsistence farmer.

00:35:05.870 --> 00:35:06.850
Because you had some food.

00:35:06.850 --> 00:35:10.400
If you were an urban or poor,
you had really no options.

00:35:10.400 --> 00:35:12.560
Because there was no
food around you.

00:35:12.560 --> 00:35:13.600
So what happened?

00:35:13.600 --> 00:35:16.190
38 countries were rioting.

00:35:16.190 --> 00:35:18.540
Some people would claim some of
the Arab Spring is related

00:35:18.540 --> 00:35:20.500
to, actually, food
price crises.

00:35:20.500 --> 00:35:21.950
These prices went up in 2008.

00:35:21.950 --> 00:35:23.340
They haven't come down.

00:35:23.340 --> 00:35:26.480
So the world is still being
faced with this sort of food

00:35:26.480 --> 00:35:27.140
price crisis.

00:35:27.140 --> 00:35:29.280
And these stocks have
not been restored.

00:35:29.280 --> 00:35:30.360
So what was going on?

