00:35:43.340 --> 00:35:44.630
Climate change.

00:35:44.630 --> 00:35:48.030
Well, there was a drought in
Australia for seven years, in

00:35:48.030 --> 00:35:49.640
the wheat growing regions
of Australia.

00:35:49.640 --> 00:35:51.350
The wheat crops collapsed.

00:35:51.350 --> 00:35:53.750
And so the wheat prices were
just going up and up and up.

00:35:53.750 --> 00:35:59.930
The stocks were falling, falling
down tremendously.

00:35:59.930 --> 00:36:04.050
Russia had a drought the winter
after the end of the

00:36:04.050 --> 00:36:06.080
Australia droughts.

00:36:06.080 --> 00:36:08.910
More crisis in the
wheat markets.

00:36:08.910 --> 00:36:11.640
So climate change suddenly is
starting to affect our global

00:36:11.640 --> 00:36:12.560
food supply.

00:36:12.560 --> 00:36:15.050
So if any of you are wondering
about whether climate change

00:36:15.050 --> 00:36:17.860
is real, believe me, in the
world we live in, and we're

00:36:17.860 --> 00:36:19.720
looking at these food supplies,
it is really real.

00:36:19.720 --> 00:36:20.910
And it's here to stay.

00:36:20.910 --> 00:36:23.710
And in places like Africa, in
various parts of it, the

00:36:23.710 --> 00:36:27.210
Somalia famine that Kristin
talked about, that was about

00:36:27.210 --> 00:36:32.010
climate change impacts in a
drought prone region, where we

00:36:32.010 --> 00:36:33.370
used to see droughts
every seven years.

00:36:33.370 --> 00:36:35.150
Now we see them every
three years.

00:36:35.150 --> 00:36:36.920
Other issue, ethanol.

00:36:36.920 --> 00:36:39.670
40% of the corn grown in
the United States goes

00:36:39.670 --> 00:36:41.010
into your gas tank.

00:36:41.010 --> 00:36:41.530
Why?

00:36:41.530 --> 00:36:44.080
Because we have legislation
in the United States that

00:36:44.080 --> 00:36:46.010
originally thought was going
to be part of a solution to

00:36:46.010 --> 00:36:48.390
the climate problem and
reducing carbon in the

00:36:48.390 --> 00:36:49.070
atmosphere.

00:36:49.070 --> 00:36:51.670
Turns out, it's not
actually the case.

00:36:51.670 --> 00:36:56.370
But we have laws now that
require 10% of every gallon of

00:36:56.370 --> 00:36:58.900
gas you put in your gas
tank is ethanol based.

00:36:58.900 --> 00:37:00.820
And that is a congressional
mandate that's

00:37:00.820 --> 00:37:02.440
going to go up to 15%.

00:37:02.440 --> 00:37:04.080
This is the first time in
history we've had a

00:37:04.080 --> 00:37:06.650
relationship between
food and fuel.

00:37:06.650 --> 00:37:08.910
And we're taking that corn out
of the global food supply.

00:37:08.910 --> 00:37:10.390
What's the implication
of that?

00:37:10.390 --> 00:37:12.990
Higher prices, because
you have less supply.

00:37:12.990 --> 00:37:16.560
So that's another sort
of a critical issue.

00:37:16.560 --> 00:37:19.680
Global oil prices, fossil
fuel, and industrial

00:37:19.680 --> 00:37:22.870
agriculture, to Diana's point.

00:37:22.870 --> 00:37:25.540
This is what has sustained us
here in the United States.

00:37:25.540 --> 00:37:27.960
But actually, it's a very
expensive way to do

00:37:27.960 --> 00:37:28.490
agriculture.

00:37:28.490 --> 00:37:30.410
And when you think about the
fact that you're going to have

00:37:30.410 --> 00:37:33.620
increasing demand for fossil
fuels globally, and that

00:37:33.620 --> 00:37:37.170
fossil fuels provide inputs for
fertilizers, pesticides,

00:37:37.170 --> 00:37:41.150
herbicides, if oil prices keep
going up and up and up, which

00:37:41.150 --> 00:37:44.000
they're predicted to do, inputs
for people like Susan

00:37:44.000 --> 00:37:46.190
are going to go up and up and
up, which take her out of the

00:37:46.190 --> 00:37:46.960
production cycle.

00:37:46.960 --> 00:37:48.560
Because she can't afford
the inputs.

00:37:48.560 --> 00:37:51.280
Which is also, if you remember,
the fuel prices went

00:37:51.280 --> 00:37:53.610
up in 2008, 2009 as well.

00:37:53.610 --> 00:37:56.860
So there were all of these
sort of confluent factors

00:37:56.860 --> 00:37:59.390
coming together that
drove this crisis.

00:37:59.390 --> 00:38:01.290
And it's still staying
with us.

00:38:01.290 --> 00:38:03.020
And these are things we've
got to keep an

00:38:03.020 --> 00:38:04.600
eye on going forward.

00:38:04.600 --> 00:38:07.730
Now, are there some things we
can be thinking about and

00:38:07.730 --> 00:38:09.220
