00:46:55.730 --> 00:47:01.510
And to that, wanted to toss it
to you about the great Oxfam

00:47:01.510 --> 00:47:02.720
Unwrapped campaign.

00:47:02.720 --> 00:47:03.200
KRISTIN DAVIS: Absolutely.

00:47:03.200 --> 00:47:05.250
This is something that
we do year round.

00:47:05.250 --> 00:47:07.700
But then occasionally, we
do talk about it more.

00:47:07.700 --> 00:47:09.160
And this is one of
those times.

00:47:09.160 --> 00:47:11.970
We do a really great project,
it's called Oxfam Unwrapped.

00:47:11.970 --> 00:47:14.540
And we have a website,
Oxfamgifts.com.

00:47:14.540 --> 00:47:16.960
And it's something where
you can go on.

00:47:16.960 --> 00:47:18.330
We have a variety of things.

00:47:18.330 --> 00:47:20.250
They are very reasonably
priced.

00:47:20.250 --> 00:47:22.530
And sometimes, you can send
a goat to someone.

00:47:22.530 --> 00:47:26.750
Or you could send worms
to help a farmer

00:47:26.750 --> 00:47:28.440
change their soil.

00:47:28.440 --> 00:47:30.510
You can send bees.

00:47:30.510 --> 00:47:34.840
Bee keeping is a very amazing
business that you can do on

00:47:34.840 --> 00:47:39.870
your own if you have the skill
and the basic beginning tools.

00:47:39.870 --> 00:47:41.370
One of the--

00:47:41.370 --> 00:47:42.150
well, not one.

00:47:42.150 --> 00:47:44.480
I've seen so many of
these items in

00:47:44.480 --> 00:47:45.600
practice on my travels.

00:47:45.600 --> 00:47:47.140
And you kind of taken them
for granted here.

00:47:47.140 --> 00:47:48.790
Like, a handful of seeds.

00:47:48.790 --> 00:47:49.930
Again, something you
think like, a

00:47:49.930 --> 00:47:51.595
handful of seeds, really?

00:47:51.595 --> 00:47:53.880
This makes a huge difference,
does it not?

00:47:53.880 --> 00:47:55.200
It is amazing.

00:47:55.200 --> 00:47:59.460
People do not have access to a
lot of the newer seeds that

00:47:59.460 --> 00:48:03.420
have been, through trial and
error, come in to these

00:48:03.420 --> 00:48:04.400
heartier seeds.

00:48:04.400 --> 00:48:06.850
And that makes a huge difference
to a small farmer.

00:48:06.850 --> 00:48:08.960
So we have the training.

00:48:08.960 --> 00:48:12.420
People go and educate the
farmers or the women about how

00:48:12.420 --> 00:48:13.450
to raise chicks.

00:48:13.450 --> 00:48:17.210
That's another amazing skill
set that is very simple.

00:48:17.210 --> 00:48:18.060
People can do it at home.

00:48:18.060 --> 00:48:19.450
You don't have to leave
your children.

00:48:19.450 --> 00:48:24.100
I've seen women have much
smaller but very similar

00:48:24.100 --> 00:48:26.390
outcomes as Susan in terms
of their husbands

00:48:26.390 --> 00:48:27.640
going no, no, no, no.

00:48:27.640 --> 00:48:30.610
And then, these are people, in
the mountains of Mozambique by

00:48:30.610 --> 00:48:33.920
Zimbabwe we met women who were
literally living on less than

00:48:33.920 --> 00:48:35.270
$2 a month.

00:48:35.270 --> 00:48:37.595
Extreme poverty is defined
as less than $2 a day.

00:48:37.595 --> 00:48:40.180
These people were living on
less than $2 a month.

00:48:40.180 --> 00:48:41.240
I mean, it was extreme.

00:48:41.240 --> 00:48:44.480
And they lived in the most
beautiful, beautiful region.

00:48:44.480 --> 00:48:45.780
We called it Shangri La.

00:48:45.780 --> 00:48:47.730
Yet, they really had nothing.

00:48:47.730 --> 00:48:49.990
And they were given
organic seeds.

00:48:49.990 --> 00:48:52.260
And they were growing lettuce
bigger than my head.

00:48:52.260 --> 00:48:53.350
They were so proud.

00:48:53.350 --> 00:48:54.690
They were living on these
steep mountains.

00:48:54.690 --> 00:48:57.020
And we taught them irrigation
methods.

00:48:57.020 --> 00:48:58.880
And then they were also
raising chicks.

00:48:58.880 --> 00:49:00.690
And the husbands had said
no, no, absolutely

00:49:00.690 --> 00:49:02.300
not, absolutely not.

00:49:02.300 --> 00:49:03.490
My wife does not work.

00:49:03.490 --> 00:49:04.530
She is the mother
of my children.

00:49:04.530 --> 00:49:07.490
Well, when they got that $20
bill at the end of the month,

00:49:07.490 --> 00:49:10.830
they were like, OK!

00:49:10.830 --> 00:49:11.936
DIANE SOLINGER: Money
talks, right?

00:49:11.936 --> 00:49:12.362
KRISTIN DAVIS: Yeah.

00:49:12.362 --> 00:49:13.930
And it was just really
wonderful.

00:49:13.930 --> 00:49:16.580
Because that woman, you could
see the pride that she took in

00:49:16.580 --> 00:49:17.630
what she had accomplished.

00:49:17.630 --> 00:49:20.610
And you would always ask the
women, we always would say,

00:49:20.610 --> 00:49:23.860
what did you do with your money
when you had finished

00:49:23.860 --> 00:49:25.140
the project and made
the money?

00:49:25.140 --> 00:49:28.660
And they would always say, I
bought the school uniform so

00:49:28.660 --> 00:49:30.330
my child could go
back to school.

00:49:30.330 --> 00:49:31.520
I bought the paper.

00:49:31.520 --> 00:49:33.430
So there are things we
take for granted.

00:49:33.430 --> 00:49:35.760
If you can't buy your
child paper, your

00:49:35.760 --> 00:49:36.860
child can't go to school.

00:49:36.860 --> 00:49:39.710
And school is often a tree
they are sitting under.

00:49:39.710 --> 00:49:40.910
That is school.

00:49:40.910 --> 00:49:43.340
But they can't go if there's
no paper or pencil.

00:49:43.340 --> 00:49:46.100
So school books are on
Oxfam Unwrapped.

00:49:46.100 --> 00:49:46.860
Really amazing things.

00:49:46.860 --> 00:49:48.550
School meals for the children.

00:49:48.550 --> 00:49:51.050
Because a lot of the time, they
don't have a good meal,

00:49:51.050 --> 00:49:53.590
which we all know you need to
eat to be able to think to be

00:49:53.590 --> 00:49:54.520
able to learn.

00:49:54.520 --> 00:49:57.610
And the next generation is going
to change the world, as

00:49:57.610 --> 00:49:58.300
my young faces now--

00:49:58.300 --> 00:49:58.870
DIANE SOLINGER: It gets
them to school.

00:49:58.870 --> 00:50:00.470
KRISTIN DAVIS: Exactly, it
gets them to school.

00:50:00.470 --> 00:50:03.520
But the little young people
here, you're so adorable.

00:50:03.520 --> 00:50:05.910
And it makes me feel hopeful
that you're all interested in

00:50:05.910 --> 00:50:06.800
these kinds of things.

00:50:06.800 --> 00:50:08.880
But when you're out in the world
you see these little

00:50:08.880 --> 00:50:10.840
kids, and you see how much their
mothers really want to

00:50:10.840 --> 00:50:12.610
send them to school,
it's really moving.

00:50:12.610 --> 00:50:14.910
And it really makes a huge, huge
difference when they are

00:50:14.910 --> 00:50:16.010
able to do so.

00:50:16.010 --> 00:50:18.570
So there's a lot of things
on Oxfam Unwrapped

00:50:18.570 --> 00:50:19.780
related to the kids.

00:50:19.780 --> 00:50:21.540
Then there's a lot related
to farmers,

00:50:21.540 --> 00:50:22.750
many of whom are women.

00:50:22.750 --> 00:50:25.920
Tools, seeds, worms.

00:50:25.920 --> 00:50:28.830
Then there's a lot like
ducks, goats, bees.

00:50:28.830 --> 00:50:31.940
